  <h1>RCV vs. ACV Explained</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Replacement cost value (RCV)</h2><p>What it costs to replace the damaged property with a new equivalent today, without deducting depreciation. If your 5-year-old roof is destroyed, RCV pays for a new roof at today&rsquo;s prices. Most homeowners policies with an RCV endorsement pay RCV for structural damage after repairs are completed (the insurer first pays ACV, then pays the &ldquo;recoverable depreciation&rdquo; after you show the replacement was made).</p>
  <h2>Actual cash value (ACV)</h2><p>Replacement cost minus accumulated depreciation. If your 5-year-old TV costs $1,000 to replace new and has depreciated $600 (60% in 5 years), ACV is $400. Auto insurance typically pays ACV for total losses. Standard (non-RCV) homeowners policies pay ACV for personal property contents.</p>
  <h2>Why it matters</h2><p>The difference between RCV and ACV can be enormous for older property. A 15-year-old HVAC system might cost $6,000 to replace new but have an ACV of only $1,500 after depreciation. Upgrading to an RCV endorsement typically costs 10–15% more in premium but pays multiples more in a significant loss.</p>
  <h2>Holdback and recoverable depreciation</h2><p>For RCV policies, insurers typically pay ACV first and hold back the depreciation (&ldquo;holdback&rdquo;) until you complete repairs and submit proof. You must actually repair or replace the damaged item to collect the holdback.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-property-damage-claims-work">how claims work</a> and <a href="/guides/property-damage-misconceptions">common misconceptions</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
